{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5393d72-8d5a-486c-a030-92944c5aa6da","content":"Two separate breaking changes in C# 15:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `left && right` with `dynamic`\n\nC# 15 now **validates the short-circuit operator pattern at compile time** even when one operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the entire expression was deferred to runtime binding.\n\n`&&` is synthesized from three operators: `operator &` + `operator true` + `operator false`. Your `IFilter` declares `true`/`false` but **no `operator &`**, so the compiler rejects it.\n\n**Fixes** (pick one):\n```csharp\n// Option A: Add the missing operator to the interface\ninterface IFilter\n{\n    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;\n    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;\n    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;\n}\n\n// Option B: Make both operands dynamic to fully defer to runtime\nvar combined = (dynamic)left && right;\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `ref readonly` lambda → CS0518\n\nCS0518 (\"predefined type not defined or imported\") means the compiler needs a BCL type that isn't present in your target framework. For `ref readonly` returns on lambdas, the compiler must synthesize a delegate type and emit a `[RequiresLocation]` attribute to encode `readonly` in metadata.\n\nThis typically happens when the **language version (C# 15) is ahead of the target framework**. Even if the SDK is .NET 11, check your `<TargetFramework>`:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Ensure this is net11.0, not an older TFM -->\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\nIf you must target an older framework, avoid the lambda form:\n\n```csharp\n// Workaround: use a named method + explicit delegate type\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\n\nprivate static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;\n\npublic static void M()\n{\n    RefReadOnlyFunc fn = GetValue;\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ccef928-9190-4d5b-957f-6872b7867e29","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases.\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a known breaking change related to how the compiler handles the `&&` (short-circuit) operator when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe `&&` operator in C# is not directly overloadable — it's synthesized from `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve these operators at compile time for the static operand's type and defer the rest to runtime.\n\n\nThe problem is that `IFilter` defines `operator true` and `operator false` as static interface members. In C# 15, the compiler changed how it handles user-defined operators on interfaces when `dynamic` is involved, and it's now stricter about resolving these operators through the interface contract rather than allowing the dynamic binding to handle it at runtime. cter compile-time checks on compound logical operators with `dynamic` operands. When the compiler encounters `left && right` where `right` is `dynamic`, it now validates at compile time that the left operand's type supports `operator true`, `operator false`, and `operator &` — but `IFilter` only has the first two, causing the compilation to fail where it previously deferred everything to runtime dynamic binding.\n\nNow looking at the second case with a `ref readonly` lambda...\n\nThe error CS0518 indicates a missing type from the framework. In C# 15 / .NET 11, `ref readonly` return types on lambdas require new runtime support — likely a compiler services attribute or a special delegate type that older frameworks don't have. The compiler can't use standard `Func<T>` or `Action<T>` delegates for ref returns, so it needs to synthesize something new, possibly involving function pointers or a dedicated delegate type that represents `ref readonly` semantics. couldn't have a lambda with `ref readonly` return. C# 15 may have added this feature but it requires a new framework type that might not be available or there's a mismatch between what the compiler expects and what the runtime provides.\n\nFor the dynamic with `&&` operator issue, this is likely a Roslyn change where the compiler now validates at compile time that the static type of `left` supports the `&&` pattern. `IFilter` has `operator true` and `operator false` but is missing `operator &`, which the compiler now requires. I could fix this by adding `operator &` to `IFilter`, casting `left` to `dynamic` as well, or replacing the `&&` with explicit logic.\n\nFor the ref readonly lambda error, the compiler is likely looking for a predefined type or BCL attribute to represent the `ref readonly` return type on a lambda delegate, which either doesn't exist or isn't available in the current framework version. This could be a new C# 15 feature that requires a specific .NET SDK and runtime version, so I'd need to either declare an explicit delegate type with `ref readonly` return, use a method instead of a lambda, or ensure the correct .NET 11 SDK and runtime are installed.\n\nThe dynamic operator issue is a breaking change where the compiler now requires the static type to have all three operators (`&`/`|`, `true`, `false`) defined, even when the other operand is `dynamic` — it no longer silently binds `&&`/`||` at runtime when it can't verify the operator pattern at compile time.\n\nFor `ref readonly` returns on lambdas, the compiler needs to synthesize a delegate type since standard `Func<>` delegates don't support ref returns. To encode the `readonly` aspect in metadata, it likely needs `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` (added in C# 12 for `ref readonly` parameters) or a similar attribute. The CS0518 error suggests the compiler is looking for a well-known type that's missing from the runtime libraries, which is puzzling if they upgraded to .NET 11 — unless this is a genuinely new feature with a tooling issue, or there's a multi-targeting scenario where one target lacks the type.\n\nThe most likely culprit is that they upgraded the compiler to C# 15 (which now properly supports `ref readonly` lambdas) but are still targeting an older runtime that doesn't have the required BCL types. The fix would be to ensure both the compiler and target framework are aligned to .NET 11.","outputTokens":3171,"requestId":"C444:3BF53A:1EC3A1E:229BC05:6A07C9A1"},"id":"54763066-6bd8-418e-9a7a-9e5a01592b18","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:35:27.679Z","parentId":"392c71ed-5bd0-4226-8ac6-33821389691d"}
